	<p>
		<term>Measuring radioactivity</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		When concerning ourselves with radioactivity and safety, it’s always important to minimize the exposure of medical personnel and patients. Radioactivity has the potential to cause chemical changes to our cells which can lead to cell death, mutations, and cancer. One of the easiest ways to minimize our risk is to use the lowest amount of radioactive isotope possible. The question then arises…how do we measure radioactivity. Radioactivity can be measured by a variety of devices, depending on the type of emission. In all cases, the SI unit that is used to measure radioactivity is a <term>becquerel</term> (abbreviated Bq), which is the same as one radioactive decay (or disintegration) every second. The nuclei of a radioactive isotope will randomly decay, releasing radioactivity. If a sample contains more nuclei or is more enriched in radioactive nuclei (ie. there are more radioactive nuclei and fewer non-radioactive nuclei) then the sample will produce more radiation every second, leading to a higher Bq value. Another historically important unit of measure for radioactivity is a <term>Curie</term> (abbreviated Ci). A Curie is a much larger quantity than a becquerel and represents 3.7 x10<sup>10</sup> decays per second or that same number of becquerels. A Curie often represents a very large amount of radiation, so it’s common for laboratory personnel to use smaller metric prefixes along with Curies, such as mCi or µCi.
	</p>

	<p>
		The units of Curies and becquerels are used to describe how much radiation an object emits. The emission of radioactivity from an object moves in all directions, and thus a large percentage of that radiation may never enter the body of a patient or medical professional. To describe the amount of radiation that actually enters the body, scientists use a different unit called a <term>rad</term>. This unit has since been replaced by the SI unit of <term>grey (</term>abbreviated Gy; one Gy is the same as 100 rad).
	</p>

	<p>
		To quantify the damaging effects of absorbed radiation, scientists use the unit <term>rem</term> (radiation equivalent in man). Rem can be easily calculated from rad by multiplying it by a damage factor that is specific to the type of radioactive particle that’s being absorbed. In general, gamma rays, beta particles, and positrons cause the least amount of damage (and thus have a factor of 1), protons and neutrons cause moderate damage (and have a factor of 10), and alpha particles cause the most damage (and have a factor of 20). Another unit that is used to measure the effect of absorbed radiation is a <term>Sievert (abbreviated Sv)</term>. One Sievert is equivalent to 100 rem. How much radiation is too much? An average person receives about 3 mSv of radiation per year. A single x-ray or a CT scan subject a person to 0.1-10 mSv of radiation. At a dose of 50 mSv, there is a statistically detectable increase in a person’s cancer risk. Radiation sickness can begin to set in with doses of 0.5 Sv (notice the change from mSv with the previous doses). A dose of 3-4 Sv is generally fatal to ~50% of people who receive that high of a dose.
	</p>

