	<p>
		<term>Radiation safety</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		Radiation can pose safety risks to humans, but if users are careful, the health impacts can be minimized. In order to avoid harm from radiation, there are 3 things to consider:
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Amount of radiation used
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Time
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Distance
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Shielding
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

	<p>
		Whenever radioactive materials or other radiation sources are used, we should be careful to use the least amount possible. As you’d expect, by using lower amounts of radioactive materials, we can lessen the total exposure to radiation as well as the total amount of possible damage.
	</p>

	<p>
		Likewise, biological damage from radiation can be lessened by spending the minimal amount of time in an environment with a radiation source. In general, the more time a person spends near a radiation source, the greater their exposure to radiation and therefore the greater the amount of biological damage that will occur.
	</p>

	<p>
		Another important consideration is the distance between the radioactive material (or radiation source) and the person being exposed. There is a mathematical relationship between the amount of radiation a person’s body absorbs and the distance from the radiation source. The intensity of radiation decreases by the square of the distance increase from the radiation source. If you are standing 2 m from a radiation source, you would receive ¼ the radiation exposure that you would receive if you were standing 1 m away. This is because the same amount of radiation becomes spread over a larger area as the distance increases. The impact of distance on radiation intensity is described by the inverse square law equation:
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>I_{2} = I_{1}\left( \frac{d_{1}}{d_{2}} \right)^{2}</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		Where <m>I_{1}</m> and <m>I_{2}</m> are the radiation intensities at the first (<m>d_{1}</m>) and second (<m>d_{2}</m>) distances respectively.
	</p>

	<p>
		Finally, various forms of radiation can be blocked by different types of shielding. In general, the larger the particle and more charged it is, the less shielding required. Alpha particles, the most massive radioactive particles, can be blocked by a sheet of paper or by our outer layer of skin. For alpha particle emitters to cause biological damage, they must typically be ingested or incorporated into the body by some other means. Beta-particles can be shielded by about a centimeter of aluminum, plastic, or plexiglass. Neutrons (no charge) and gamma rays (no mass or charge) are much more difficult to shield. Radioactive sources that emit these forms of radiation often require lead or concrete shielding to block exposure.
	</p>

