	<p>
		<term>Half-life on radioisotopes</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		Radioactive isotopes decay in a random fashion. As they decay, the atoms in the sample change and the sample can gradually lose its radioactive properties, simply because there is less and less of the original radioactive isotope left. We measure the decay rate of radioactive isotopes using <term>half-lives.</term> One half life is the amount of time required to have the decay rate of a substance decrease by a factor of one-half. So after one half life, half of the original isotope remains and the decay rate will thus be ½ of what it originally was. After a second half life has passed, one-half of one-half of the original radioactive isotope will remain (or ¼). After each subsequent half-life the amount of original radioactive isotope will again decrease by ½. We can use this information to derive a formula to calculate the amount of radioactive isotope or the decay rate after a given amount of time has passed:
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>R_{t} = R_{0} \times \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{t/t_{\frac{1}{2}}\ }</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		In this formula <m>R_{t}</m> is the decay rate or amount of isotope at time t and <m>R_{0}</m> is the original rate or amount. The variables <m>t</m> and <m>t_{\frac{1}{2}}</m> represent the time that has passed and the half-life of the isotope respectively. So if we began with 17 mCi of radioactive material that has a half-life of 8 days and 30 days have passed, we’d have <m>17 \times \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{\frac{30}{8}} = 1.3\ </m>mCi of radioactive material left. Half lives of isotopes can vary dramatically with short ones having half-lives of seconds or minutes and long ones having half-lives of thousands of years. Isotopes that are used clinically generally have short half-lives (on the order of days or weeks) because that means that they will decay at a fast rate meaning that they can produce their useful radiation dose more quickly with less material required.
	</p>

